## Executive Summary

Germany’s Federal Foreign Office is a major humanitarian donor,
providing substantial funding with significant year-to-year and regional
variability. Its funding portfolio is marked by strategic geographic
diversification, expanding the number of recipient countries markedly
from 2022 to 2025. While total disbursements show volatility and fewer
but larger transactions compared to peers, this allows for impactful,
large-scale interventions. Germany exhibits a distinctive earmarking
pattern, prioritizing specific regions and themes, which should guide
tailored proposal development. Fundraisers should leverage Germany’s
expanding reach and episodic high-value contributions, while advocating
for more predictable, balanced allocations aligned with evolving
humanitarian priorities to optimize program stability and donor
engagement.

## Volatility

The analysis of funding transactions recorded for Germany’s Federal
Foreign Office highlights notable characteristics compared to other top
donors. With 222 recorded transactions, Germany averages 74.0
transactions per year at an average value of 3.1 million USD each. This
is higher per transaction than the benchmark of the top 10 other donors,
whose average transaction amount is 2.8 million USD, but their average
transaction frequency is substantially higher at 387.2 per year. Over
the recorded time span from March 2023 to December 2025, the transaction
values fluctuate significantly, with a wide range from under one million
to several tens of millions USD. The funding pattern presents volatility
with noticeable peaks and troughs in disbursed amounts, indicating
periods of concentrated funding activity rather than consistent
disbursement flow. This volatility and lower transaction frequency may
affect planning stability for humanitarian operations and require
flexible financial management. For proposal writers, these findings
suggest opportunities to advocate for more regular and predictable
funding streams from Germany to align better with operational needs and
reduce risk. Additionally, the comparatively higher average transaction
value might be leveraged to promote strategic, high-impact interventions
that require larger lump-sum funding. Understanding Germany’s
distinctive funding profile will aid in tailoring proposals and resource
mobilization efforts to match donor behavior and optimize collaboration.
